  "why": "The paper goes beyond reporting failure-triggering inputs (ETIs) and provides diagnostic analysis that links discovered failures to underlying model vulnerabilities. Concretely, the authors (1) explain failures as arising from incorrect/ill-separated decision boundaries (a root cause), (2) show that ETIs cluster by transformation into ‘‘erroneous properties’’ (EPs) and that testing can become ‘‘trapped’’ in a few EPs (analysis of failure patterns), (3) quantify pervasive mutual exclusivity between transformations (a structural model weakness) and show how this causes fine-tuning to degrade resilience for some transformations, and (4) measure per-transformation fine-tuning loss and random-attack success rate (RASR) to demonstrate and diagnose which EPs are neglected or worsened. They then propose and evaluate a targeted mitigation (EP-oriented testing and per-transformation fine-tuning) that directly addresses the diagnosed vulnerabilities. These elements together link observed failures to specific internal/model-level vulnerabilities and provide actionable guidance for repair, matching the “High” level in the metric.",
